<Layout
  title="peek vs Jam.dev"
  description="peek vs Jam.dev: a free, open-source, local-first way to capture a browser bug and hand your AI agent a Playwright repro. No account, no cloud upload."
>
  <h1>peek vs Jam.dev</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Both record rich context from your real browser. The delta is the
    consumer: peek hands your AI coding agent forensic read access to debug
    what already happened; Jam hands a human engineer a shareable bug report.
  </p>

  <p>
    This page exists for the person searching &ldquo;jam.dev alternative&rdquo;
    or &ldquo;local-only bug capture&rdquo; or &ldquo;MCP browser
    extension.&rdquo; No FUD &mdash; Jam.dev is a well-built product. The two tools
    overlap in tech but target different workflows. The sections below say
    when each one fits.
  </p>

  <h2>At a glance</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th></th>
        <th>peek</th>
        <th>Jam.dev</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Primary consumer</strong></td>
        <td>An AI coding agent (Claude Code, Cursor, Cline, Windsurf, Continue, Zed) querying via MCP.</td>
        <td>A human engineer reviewing a bug report sent by QA / a PM / a designer.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Output format</strong></td>
        <td>MCP tools returning JSON (console errors, network failures, DOM-at-timestamp, full event slices). The session lives in a local SQLite DB.</td>
        <td>A &ldquo;Jam&rdquo; &mdash; a hosted URL with rendered video + DOM + console + network for a human viewer.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Where data lives</strong></td>
        <td>Local: <code>~/.peek/sessions.db</code>. Never leaves your machine.</td>
        <td>Vendor cloud (jam.dev). Required for the shareable URL workflow.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Signup</strong></td>
        <td>None. Install the CLI + extension and go.</td>
        <td>Required (Jam account) to host and share captures.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Cost</strong></td>
        <td>Free. Apache 2.0.</td>
        <td>Free tier with limits; paid tiers for teams.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Workflow shape</strong></td>
        <td>You're already talking to your AI agent. You ask &ldquo;what's in my latest session?&rdquo; The agent calls <code>list_sessions</code>, <code>get_session_console_errors</code>, etc. and answers.</td>
        <td>You hit the Jam button, narrate a bug, click stop, paste the URL into Slack. The recipient signs in and reviews the rendered capture.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Capture trigger</strong></td>
        <td>Per-origin host permission. Off by default for every site. Enable from the side panel.</td>
        <td>Click the Jam extension button to start, click again to stop.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Replay UX</strong></td>
        <td>None in the extension &mdash; AI agents query the data structurally. (Optional <code>peek sessions export --format html</code> writes a tracelane-style file for human viewing.)</td>
        <td>Purpose-built reviewer UI: video timeline, DOM inspector, console pane, network pane, commenting.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Network capture</strong></td>
        <td>Yes (rrweb + optional CDP &ldquo;Deep capture&rdquo; for response bodies).</td>
        <td>Yes.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Console capture</strong></td>
        <td>Yes (level + stack + URL).</td>
        <td>Yes.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Write-back</strong></td>
        <td>The MCP surface defines <code>execute_action</code> (click / input / navigate) gated by per-action authorization + an audit log. The permission model and audit log ship today; the cross-process bridge that delivers actions to the live browser is in development (read-only until it lands). Off by default; not a sharing feature.</td>
        <td>Read-only by design &mdash; Jam is a capture-and-share product, not a remote-control tool.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Privacy boundary</strong></td>
        <td>Your machine. Sessions, audit log, native messaging host all local.</td>
        <td>Vendor cloud (Jam's infrastructure). Vendor SOC2 + their data-handling policy.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>MCP-native</strong></td>
        <td>Yes &mdash; this is the entire design goal.</td>
        <td>No. Jam is a browser-extension + cloud product; AI-agent integration isn't its target.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Maturity</strong></td>
        <td>Pre-1.0 (alpha). Available on the Chrome Web Store; can also be loaded unpacked for development.</td>
        <td>Mature commercial product with significant team adoption.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>When peek is the right choice</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>The primary thing you do with browser context is <em>talk to your AI agent about it</em> &mdash; you want Claude Code / Cursor / Cline to read what's on the page when you describe a problem.</li>
    <li>You're under local-only constraints &mdash; regulated industry, sensitive customer data, contractual requirement that &ldquo;recordings of our app don't leave employee machines.&rdquo;</li>
    <li>You want the option of <em>write-back</em> (an AI agent that can click and type for you on the live tab) with explicit per-action authorization. peek's permission model is built for this; Jam doesn't address it.</li>
    <li>You're OSS-first and don't want a vendor in the audit log for your bug data.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When Jam.dev is the right choice</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Your primary workflow is <em>handoff</em>: someone captures a bug; someone else fixes it. The capturer (QA, PM, designer, support) is often not the fixer (engineer). Jam's hosted URL collapses that into one link.</li>
    <li>You want a polished hosted reviewer UX out of the box &mdash; commenting, sharing, video scrubbing, organization-level capture libraries.</li>
    <li>The data crossing into vendor cloud is acceptable to your security review.</li>
    <li>You don't (yet) have an AI-coding-agent workflow that benefits from MCP &mdash; Jam's value prop is human-to-human.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Can you use both?</h2>

  <p>
    Yes. They don't conflict. Use Jam for &ldquo;here's a bug, please fix&rdquo;
    handoffs to a teammate, and peek for &ldquo;here's what's in my browser,
    Claude, please help me work this out.&rdquo; Different workflows, no
    overlap in storage or replay.
  </p>

  <h2>What about Sentry Session Replay or LogRocket?</h2>

  <p>
    Different category. Both Sentry Session Replay and LogRocket record
    <em>production traffic</em> from end-users &mdash; the captures are about
    incidents your users hit, not about bugs you're actively poking. peek is
    a developer-side tool: nothing records until you explicitly enable it on
    a specific site, and the captures live on your machine, not in a product
    data warehouse. If you need production-incident replay, Sentry / LogRocket
    are the right shape. Peek does not compete in that category.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this page exists</h2>

  <p>
    Comparison pages capture search intent that the competitor's own marketing
    page deliberately won't. If you arrived here from
    &ldquo;jam.dev alternative,&rdquo; the honest answer is: it depends on
    whether your primary consumer of the capture is an AI agent or a human.
    peek is purpose-built for the first; Jam is purpose-built for the second.
  </p>

